					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">When I wrote <a href="https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/1101008925/lizard/posts/1582636" class="postlink">an article about NES sprites</a>, my best example for efficient/effective use of 8x8 sprites was Blaster Master's Sophia III:<br /><div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<a href="./download/file.php?id=9572&amp;mode=view"><img src="./download/file.php?id=9572&amp;t=1" alt="ex1_blaster.gif" /></a><br />
			<span class="gensmall">ex1_blaster.gif [ 12.34 KiB | Viewed 985 times ]</span>
		

		<br />
	</div><br /><br />Of course, Blaster Master uses 8x16 for the interior game segments where the characters are bigger.<br /><br />The only critical issue in my view is that 8x16 becomes necessary once you want a certain amount of screen coverage. Everything else besides that seems a minor/manageable issue, and pretty debatable which is better.<br /><br />8x8 for the micro managers, detailed control, efficient use of tile space, etc. (with no CHR-banking it seems helpful in that respect).<br /><br />8x16 for coarse and easy control.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

